It's not that difficult, at least in principle. First, select all the vertices in your object you want hair coming out of (so I don't know how you've done it, but if things like eyes and whatnot are separate objects, select the verticies on the nipples and then do select-invert). Create a vertex group, call it something clever like "furry_bits". Now add a material to your object that you want to use for the hair. Go into "modifier properties" (wrench icon). Add Modifier > Particle System. Now go to "particle properties" (icon that looks like a ball with three other balls coming out of it). Change it from "emitter" to "hair." Under "render", you can now assign your fur material. (Now you can have the skin have a different texture from the fur!) Down under "vertex groups" pick pretty much any of the options and select your "furry_bits" group. Now just start messing around with the properties of the hair. Blender is occasionally quite weird and frustrating when you try to tamper with some of the settings, so you'll have to play around, but clearly you'll want a decent number of emitters and a fairly short length. I believe that under "children," you can do clever things to avoid needing a buttload of individual hairs. See how it goes. Good luck.
